author: @blueotter5954
message:
I have a confession to make...

I remember a few months ago that I was humming this tune, and my friend was looking at me suspiciously like I was casting the most unfathomable spell. They asked me if I ever listened to the "Confessions of a Rotten Girl, and I was taken aback, because that's just not something you just say regardless of how close you are with someone. I guess my friend realized that they forgot to mention that they ment a song, or Miku, or even vocaloid, because they too became flustered from embarrassment (or shame). 

Let me tell you the truth. I was humming this song, but not because I heard the whole thing, but because I watched a Short that had this song. I watched a mini video that was a duet battle between this little Otaku Miku and Kapi the Cat(think Friday Night Funkin mods). 

Beethoven would be shaken in his boots by his modern fans: Furries, Otakus, Game Developers, Vocaloid Artists.

author: @lumimaruu
message:
Probably a detail someone pointed out, but if you play the song around 2:55 - 2:56, you can see a few frames of Miku looking worried, as if she's aware that the viewer (or viewers,) is leaving her during that moment. The final frame before the glitching stops shows Miku facing away; I personally think this is Miku going to sit down, waiting for the viewer to return, as when it cuts back to her, she is sitting down before realizing the viewer is back.
(Clarifying, these frames are before she starts talking about how she hopes the viewer won't leave for long, or change the channel.)

EDIT: When Miku repeats "Now and forever," you can see a single frame of her with TV sets. It looks like she's crying, to me. Another frame shows her with crayons, Miku is holding a red crayon and a green one is broken.

Another edit: I'm pretty sure someone else mentioned this, but there's a frame (around when Miku says "Just stay here a while with me" a second time,) that shows a realistic-like miku. Another one shows Miku with balloons.

author: @nuclear_0
message:
Show more to find all the things I noticed in this song!!!
In 1:30 to 1:40 Miku misses the number 7, and 7 means lucky or heavenly... Won't this mean something???
Also in the scene 1:58 to 2:00 where it glitches, Miku is shown with 5 televisions, one of them being on her head. That could link to the CRT...
Also at exactly 2:28 when it glitches yet again, Miku is seen, scared. She has a face like :| and her eyes are open wide, eyebrows in a frightened state.
AND at 2:55 or 2:56 Miku is again shown scared.
AAAAND at 3:29 Miku is shown SCARED YET AGAIN, seriously what is wrong with this song and scared faces???
In 1:37, I can't describe what Miku is holding, but it's some orange stuff and then flowers on it with the flowers fading away... Doesn't that mean something of the song name being Static?
And at 1:37 again, Miku is shown with 6 books in one of each color: Red, Green, Blue, Pink, Cyan and White. If you include black and white, it's the CRT "Static/Error" colors!
At 1:06 [66 seconds, and 666 is the demon number...] Miku says "it's magic" which means the devil is magical... HOW DID I FIND THIS-
At 0:05 to 0:25 Miku says "1,2,3" 3 times, if we do 1+2+3 that equals 6. If she said it 3 times, then its 666 - the demon's number.
Final one I'm doing - At 1:31 Miku is shown grabbing a red phone, when there's blue, green, yellow, cyan and pink colors aswell. It's on a red table and Miku seems to be standing infront of it to our sight, as her hand is behind the bottom of the table on our viewpoint.

author: @oksure9261
message:
Notes:

The studio seats Miku continues referring to are completely empty, yet she displays them proudly with a spotlight regardless, seemingly obsessed with the idea that they *used* to be full.

Near the beginning, in the first glitch, Miku begins repeating the words "It's just another day" twice in quick succession. I think this because she feels as though each consecutive day is continuing on faster, without her. Also, I think it's her trying to be convince herself that nothing's changed, just another day of being beloved.

During the 2:00 glitch, two scenes stand out; Miku on the floor, drawing on the floor with multicolor crayons. Several seem to be broken. As well, Miku standing behind an arch of multicolored televisions. Looking closely, I think she may be crying? Not really smart enough to analyze the first scene, but if I'm right about what's happening in the second, the meaning is clear.

At 1:50, the aspect ratio increases so as to contain the lyrics, from what I assume is the antiquated 4:3 to what I assume is modern 16:9, what I see as an attempt to modernize to some degree so as to maintain relevance, albeit in a very shallow way.

author: @enigmaticalarrias7684
message:
I love this song so much for a myriad of reasons (the music is a banger, the style is so cute with dips into unsettling moments, many of the analystic comments), but one I noticed is how it references old syles of tv media over the decades!!
The biggest one is Miku's appearance itself, she looks veey much like the "UPA Style", which was a late 1940's/early 1950's graphic style, made to contrast the more 'realistic' style of Disney and Warner Bros. animation, with it's stronger emphasis on shapes than anatomy. She even has key points of cutoffs- big bowtie, large cuffs, and big skirt, which in the original UPA style was done to seperate the cells so the focal point of animation can be done seperately to save time/money as opposed to animating the whole character (characters like The Flinstones or Yogi Bear are examples of this, look to the latter with his collar and tie). Her more animated movements and smear frames is much more like the "UPA revival" era from the 1990's/2000's, with shows like PPG and Dexter's Lab where advancements in tech and more money being invested into TV cartoons allowed for more dynamic movement. The backgrounds are more abstract with little to no outlines, looking more like overlayed cutouts- very common in UPA styles and better defines the characters.
Miku both mentions and leans on a CRT TV, one of the earliest forms of a TV set. Big, boxy, glass screens you can feel the static from if it was on. The early commercial CRT TVs were made in 1934, with a boom post WW2, though TVs existed since late 1920's, and cathode ray tubes were first proven to used to display images in 1897! CRT TVs held strong for many decades until the 2000's, when flat screen TVs, plasma or LCD make, started taving over.
Early in the song Miku mentions the "silver screen", a common nickname for cinemas and theaters, which is how many cartoons were watched before TVs became widespread. People would purchase tickets to watch Disney, Warner Bros, or Universal animations this way, and why you can find many old posters advertising classic shorts. And it can go back even farther, with theater production bring one of the oldest forms of entertainment!
In the chorus Miku mentions studio seats and the sign off, both relating to old broadcasting, though both still continue in practice. Studio seats refer to the in-studio audience of people watching the production of shows, skits, and news reports, and can go back further for radio shows. Studio seats can also refer to the ones runing the production, but the case for the song it's heavy on the audience aspect. Sign off refers to when before TV stations pucked up 24 hour broadcasting in the 1980's-90's (though not every channel), there were notifications of when the channel was closing for the night, in forms of an annoucement, a montage, or a test pattern (color bars or the "Please Stand By" image) before static took over. Typically this was done because the transmitter equiment needed maintinence.

Realising all of this, these nods also tie into the themes of static both song-wise and theme-wise. Food for thought!

author: @Frankie-Thunderkitten
message:
Something that I really love about this song is that, much like Welcome Home and other media in this genre, is that it never goes into hardcore horror, even when Iâ€™m really expecting it. Thereâ€™s no â€˜haha nostalgic childhood thing turns scary gottem!â€™, no jumpscare, no big and flashy reveal, just the tragedy of something being very wrong that the characters are trying to tell you about, but they know youâ€™re watching and donâ€™t want to push you away, so they canâ€™t be too scary, just unsettling. And in the unsettling moments, the art and overall vibe is used as a cover of sorts so the horror is lost on the viewers. In fact, they might be using the horrors of these situations to get your attention - it has to be just â€˜offâ€™ enough so that youâ€™ll be intrigued, stay, and (maybe) help them.

Also, I love how the entire song lasts 4:04 minutes, as in a 404 error, implying that this cartoon is a piece of lost media and you werenâ€™t even supposed to FIND it, much less watch it (not that Miku cares or even realizes - for all she knows viewership on her show has simply gone done)

author: @whythis2341
message:
I'm a little late but for people who may not be familiar, it's an Osomatsu san reference! The show is a comedy, essentially about sextuplets refusing to grow up, become proper adults, and move on with their lives, grappling to the fame of their original show back in 1980s. Here's a break down of some of the references.

- There's a voice clip of the show where they say "This is how it should be." or "Kore de ii no da" on 2:27 The line in english was also repeated multiple times in the song as the motif. 6 also is a reoccurring number (6 Mikus, 6 seats being lit up).

- There's 2 main color order in this video: The first is red cyan green indigo yellow and pink. This one is simple, it's their birth order of each of the brothers, which is Osomatsu, Karamatsu, Choromatsu, Ichimatsu, Jyushimatsu, and Todomatsu in that order. Appears most commonly in the chorus where she signs out DON'T GO in sailor body language. We will get to the other order later, as that goes into spoilers.

- In the Japanese captions, the first half of each of the brother's names appeared briefly in hiragana or katakana before changing into kanji or hiragana. Oso on 0:49 , Kara on 1:12 , Choro on 2:09 , Ichi on 1:09 , Jyushi on 0:59 , and Todo on 1:51

- This is huge spoilers territory, but there is an episode that deviates from their usual comedy into a more somber tone, where one of them landed a job and ended up moving out, causing the rest of the brothers to follow suit, except for the title character, Osomatsu, who has the most trouble grappling with moving on with his life to the point of becoming apathetic and ended up staying home, he is represented by the color red. Miku in some of the shots is holding the red object (The books, the cards, and the crayons), sometimes entirely absent from the objects (TVs), and red is the background of all of these shots. Red here is meant to represent Osomatsu who refused to let go and is struggling to cling onto the past, like Miku.

- The second order of colors in those 1 frame shots is Green Pink Cyan Yellow and Indigo, with Miku holding onto the red (The books stack from top to bottom and the cards from right to left). This represents the order each of the brothers left. Choromatsu, represented by Green, leaving was the inciting incident, and thus comes first, and it's also why the Green crayon is broken. Todomatsu, Karamatsu, Jyushimatsu, and Ichimatsu eventually followed, as they couldn't handle Osomatsu's refusal to accept change.



There are a few more straight forward references such as Miku's outfit being very similar to their suits, and the song being posted on the sextuplet's birthday, but the ones I listed are the most prominent ones.

author: @le_roi_renard
message:
I do have a theory that this song is also about toxic fans who don't accept that their idol becomes more outspoken on political matters, or their idols changing to become "woke", and the moment their idol started displaying such behaviours they immediately try to discredit them by painting them as a "villain", while flocking to another "hero" after said "hero" cancelled their former idol. And the cycle repeats.

Or in other words this song is about fans who want their idols to simply "shut up and entertain us" while ignoring that their idols are human beings who can change, clinging onto their ideal images of them and deciding to dump them afterwards when it's clear that there's no going back. Think, popular artists or VTubers, or even celebrities like Taylor Swift and Chappell Roan, who started off as not saying much about political matters and/or not being "woke". But the moment they "got the woke mind virus" their entire fanbase turned their back on them, basically acting like "you no longer cater to us", "you no longer relate to us", "there's no place for darkness",... And thus they harassed the idol to the point the idol quits (or even worse, killing themselves) and they flock to another one, proclaiming them to be their "hero". Hence, "SuperHERO or DIE", either you be our "superhero", either you stay who you are supposed to be, your same old ignorant self, you shut up and sing, you stay our circus monkey,... or you die.

At least that's my two cents to it.

EDIT: After revisiting another song of his, "Magical Girl and Chocolate", I feel like these two songs can be antitheses to each other, one is about the toxic fans who wanted their idols to behave in a certain way for them, to "shut up and sing", while the other is about said idol who got sick of how those so-called "fans" treated them they decided to call it quits, or even worse, killing themselves.
Plus, the two songs' BPMs are nearly the same, Magical Girl and Chocolate being 150 and this song being 155, which further shows the feeling of the idol being "out of touch" with their fans.

author: @Wrathful_Banette
message: Commenting again because I have no self-restraint, but a detail I really like is that there's no difference in her expression and pose in her "super hero" design and her "super villain" design. Obviously there's an artistic reason behind this, so they can have both appearances swap seamlessly in the video, but it also shows how very little actually *changed* about her other than how she was perceived. It makes sense; since the beginning of the song, she's singing about how she's disconnected from the masses, while actively destroying the little chibi versions of her which represent the masses.

author: @blueseraph8618
message:
My autistic ass analyzed the lyrics to Gorgon so here's my interpretation 

"Dissolve the stone"

Reminds me of masking where you pretend to be normal and hide your disability under a normal facade, so "breaking the stone" means not masking and being true to yourself

This lyric ties into the theme of expressionless statues and not showing your true self that's underneath the stone

"Break free of the evil eye" is really interesting to me. I think it's talking about how some people get over their fear of judgment from others that leaves them exposed, aka the "evil eye" 

It sounds like something from the perspective of someone with autism who can't read other people's emotions and feelings very well and yearns to stop masking and break free of judgment

author: @PeggyWhynowhy
message:
This song hurts a lot, but in a very cathartic way. Different from how the other song hurt, in a way that made old wounds sting worse. It's astounding how quickly you were able to make this, and it's brave. This is a subject often shunned and silenced despite how many people who grew up in anime and vocaloid-adjacent communities online had to live it. "You still laugh thinking that it's funny, there's many people who would hate to see me like this"

Despite this, part of me is still torn by the usage of a real child's voice being used here.  I think it all just comes back to the ethics of a voicebank of a child existing at all, and not your fault. It isn't really something I considered until this entire debacle (hell I kinda forgot Kaai Yuki existed). Can a child consent to having their voice used for anything and everything the same way an adult can? Of course, there is certain terms of use for this exact reason. My feelings on it are pretty gray.

At the end of the day though, this song still struck a chord with me and I thank you for it regardless.

message:
The amount of cope I am seeing for this song not being suggestive lolicon is absolute insanity.

Are y'all really so lazy as to not google what the word "é›‘é­š" means? Just wiktionary is fine. If you wanna be fancy google "é›‘é­šã€€æ„å‘³" and look at niconico's or pixiv's (yes THE niconico and THE pixiv) dictionaries. Any dictionary whatsoever (assuming they collect slang, most dictionaries do that now but make sure) will say "dried fish" and "meaningless phrase used by mesukagi's" alongside each other. é›‘é­š by itself can not refer to someone as 'loser' without any connotation. It is exclusively associated with the mesugaki trope. And I cant put the definiton of mesugaki here for reasons youll understand if you search up its meaning.

And yes å¤‰æ…‹ means pervert. It does occasionally mean weirdo, just like how english speaking people may use the word pervert to jokingly refer to someone doing something sus, but you can obviously tell from that translating it as 'weirdo' is disingenious. It originally was not used to refer to a person at all- the current meaning of pervert is slang and a shortening of a phrase meaning "abnormally (the word's non-slang meaning is 'abnormal' or 'transformation') high libido" (although that phrase itself is now archaic and no longer used). There is no way in the 10 circles of hell you can tell me calling someone "abnormally high libido" in an informal and slang manner is not suggestive.

If you dont like lolicon, feel free to... just... go away. Dont force your moral nonsensing on us. You're worse than the twitter people. They know its lolicon and they dont like it because of that. Thats principle, I disagree and hate them for it but I can respect it. You like it but dont want to admit to yourself its lolicon so you exercise in mental gymnastics. Youre just spineless.

author: @Zaniel39
message:
I can't say it well in Japanese, but I've been listening to Yuuyu's music for about 15 years. Somehow, I didn't understand it until recently, but the songs he made back then and the songs he makes today both sound like they suit both the older and modern vocaloid generation. His new songs feel like they could have came out in 2010s, but they also feel modern. His old songs feel like they could come out today and still become immensely popular. I feel that Yuuyu is rarely mentioned when people talk about influential and iconic VocaP's, but his old, new, and remake songs consistently stand out to me on his ability. Somehow this remake keeps the fun of a song that came out in the early days of vocaloid, but it's still fun and fresh to listen to as someone who keeps up constantly with new songs. Still one of my favorite producers!

I hope you'll check out his newer songs as well as remakes, and I hope Yuuyu continues to make wonderful music ğŸ™

author: @l1sya._
message:
If the pebbles are piled up, higher and higher,
My heart, exposed to the wind, will become the dusk.
Someday I'll find it, if I can still find it
 white, sweet, pale
I've been playing nothing but this game of "stepping on shadows",
Searching for the stepping stone to atonement.
Someday I'll find it, if I still find it,
 long, fragile, far away

The you through the looking glass,
And the me within your eyes...

You, within someone's mind,
Are dreaming whilst in broken fragments.
And yet, you can't be deceived by this D/N/A at all!
This heart within me is crimson.
Dyed crimson.

I'm not like a sleepless lost child who's asking for too much.
Love and hate is carved into this very cell.
You are still looking for it? Am I still looking for it?
The sound I couldn't let out?

You, within someone's mind,
Are dreaming while still being connected.
And yet, this D/N/A can't explain you at all!
This pain within me, as well, is crimson.
Dyed crimson.

The figure within the mirror
And the upside-down D/N/A,
The proof of my existence
And the warm D/N/A.

The figure within the mirror
And the upside-down D/N/A,
The proof of my existence
And the warm D/N/A.

author: @rairaur2234
message:
After spending an hour reading about the whole situation, I have to say this is all so petty and tiresome. 
I feel like most of the "offended" parties never dabbled into the otaku media beyond watching Naruto. 
This is such a mild song, even popular romcom manga is more "bad."

The only real valid point in the whole argument is the origin of the voicebank, but even then, so what, it's not like this work directly references the source. 
The voice in this video has gone through so many layers of relation that it's literally disconnected from the source by any stretch of the imagination.
That's like saying that since the paintbrush was made by somebody, whatever is drawn using it reflects upon that somebody. Ridiculous.

author: @JOHNSKTR
message:
Just gonna clarify to all the certified moralist:
1. This song is clearly just teasing and playful banter, you guy are the one overreacting and so sensitve.
2. A voicebank is a recorded tool, and once created, it exists separately from the person who recorded it. Just because someone finds something "weird" does not mean it is inherently wrong or unethical. If the voice provider had no issue with the recordings being made, (which they haven't made a statement on this particular song) then your concern is purely one of personal discomfort rather than a moral failing. If using a childâ€™s voice later in unrelated contexts is considered inappropriate, then major voice-acting projects featuring children would have also have to be banned. Many famous child actors and singers have their work used long after they have grown upâ€”should their performances also be restricted because of potential NSFW associations?
3. It's always the westerns that start these stupid age and art arguments. They must feel superior when being the "moralist" snowflake they are hm?
4. GO DEFEND ACTUAL CHILDREN INSTEAD OF FICTIONAL CHARACTER/VOICE IF YOU CARE ABOUT THEIR SAFETY SO MUCH (genuinely crashing out)

message:
I like the song but the subtitles are too "Aesthetic looking". It would be nice to have a more regular style for subtitles since at the end of the day they are an accessibility feature.  Seeing the subtitles constantly moving around and changing colours could make it unreadable to some people who have dyslexia, trigger epilepsy (unless the flashing in the video triggers it first), or if the colours are too similar it could be hard for a colour blind person to read.

Edit: I didn't realise there was a plain subtitles option. I know now

message:
crappy interpretation cus I didn't focus on the lyric and vibed on the music: what I'm very sure is that the song is about social media, which i'm guessing from the use of speech bubbles, phones and literally the sm apps at the start, and maybe (??) she's compaining about sm. I think the mv goes like dis: that 1990s looking miku is doing the usual posting on social media (like photos of rndm stuff ppl put, idk i dont use it that much), and she wants to be noticed by other ppl, but she is always getting that '0 likes' no reaction. I'm 80% sure that she is asking to not get hate comments (00:41), talking about being lonely is the best but its psycho etc (idk much about that bit so let time resolve that). 
at 01:21, I think she wants to be recognized to the extent that even hate comments r allowed, then the mv hits that insane cd rewind that and starts ranting about how there is too many ppl in sm so she can't be seen. ALSO she is crazy addicted to social media, that prolly says something but again, let time resolve this cus my brain isnt braining enough for this. I think there is some evidence of attachment/love to Teto(?) but yh figure it out.
I literally might've interpreted this so wrongly so don't trust my words. its like just over 2am rn so my brain is cooked.

author: @Cyvia7
message:
Unpopular opinion :
For me, this version is answering the previous one.

The previous was more into wanting to see the other person's suffering to feel they're loved.

This one's more into "give me your suffering, because I want you to love me".

The first refrain is exactly the same between the two versions, but when we come to the last one, it has those different lyrics. But when the last echo start, I read the lyrics at the same time, the start is the same too... But it changes at the end, I can't hear nothing else than the "kurushinde" from the very first version.

Sorry if it isn't clear I tried my best to explain my thought, but I'll be happy to know yours too!

author: @oldaccountlmaox
message:
I first heard this song when I was a kid, having a difficult relationship with my dad. I saw that in the lyrics and cried. This song stuck with me for a long time.

I'm now 25 years old, my dad died 3 years ago now. I found out about this version and expected nothing to be different. The new lyrics in the bridge have me in tears again now.

I'm probably misunderstanding this song, I only speak English, sorry. I'm just having a lot of strong feelings right now.

author: @lienLe-hq2yq
message:
It's been so long since I last heard this song. I think I was still in secondary school back then and new to Vocaloid. I never expected to see a Reloaded version of Crime and Punishment. When YouTube first recommended it to me, I had to double-check the upload date. I was like, "Wait, what? Three days ago? Not a few years ago???"

Also love the little change in the lyrics. It started all the same but the small changes in the phrasing give 2 versions different meanings. 

The first one shifted from the singer's desire for love to finding satisfaction from the other personâ€™s suffering, signaling a descent into obsession or even cruelty. This shift makes the first version feel more unhinged. Especially since I remember reading some theories that the singer committed suicide to see the "you" character's "face twisted in pain" at the end of the lyrics.

The reloaded version leans more toward longing and desperation. From the beginning of the song till the end, the singer's ultimate desire remains love and connection. They express pain and despair at being unloved, their inability to draw "love" from the "you" character creates a sense of emotional helplessness. Yet their yearning for love remains the same. Thereâ€™s even a hint of acceptance when they sing, "I'd choose this world again and again," suggesting a more hopeful ending compared to the first version.

Personally, if I had to choose which version fits the song's rhythm and theme better, Iâ€™d still go with the darker original. But at the same time, the fact that this Reloaded version was released so many years laterâ€”with lyrics that feel a bit more hopefulâ€”is meaningful in its own way.

author: @existentialdreadtaco
message:
I CAN'T BELIEVE IT! â¤â¤â¤  this is GENUINELY my favorite song ever since i first heard it, and IT GOT REMASTERED!!! i was worried maybe this song got forgotten about.

when i first found this song, it meant a lot to me because i was starting to realize my patterns when it comes to attachments with people and recognize my lack of emotional regulation. i didn't know how to talk about those things without feeling weird, so this song helped me feel less alone. even now i'm still navigating those feelings, and i can fall back away from things i've learned to help me, but this song is always there to remind me i'm not alone. the dynamic switch from the more calm albeit anxious verses to the chaotic and dramatic choruses reflected the mood swings, coupled with the lyrics that switch between a simple "what can i do to get you to even look at me" to the drastic "what purpose do i even have to live if you don't love me?" the original captured my feelings from vocals to instrumental and so does the reloaded version. i'm eternally grateful for deco*27's music.

It feels more like she realised the pain she's causing ( at the end of the original) but decide to stay and " ignore " or rather take all the pain on her " pour it all into me this pain " "I'll chose this world over and over again"
She would rather stay in this circle of pain than going to a world where the other hate her, continuing this over and over again
At the end you can still here the original lyric
Seeing the pain on his face proves the person care about her, if she feel this pain then the love is there.

This is more likely my own interpretation,  but I can't bring myself to find a happy ending in it

author: @dexterousli
message:
I wonder if the MILGRAM project has played a role in inspiring DECO*27 to remake this song. A lot of people disliked Kazui's Yowamushi Montblanc cover...but I found it very nice. A lot of the changed lyrics and animation motifs in this reloaded version seem to reflect some of the themes in Kazui's character, which makes sense because OTOIRO is also working on the MILGRAM project. 

This isn't to say I think this has become a character theme, though. I'm curious as to whether the themes of regret, loneliness, and temptation present in Kazui's story and the fact that Takeuchi performed a cover of this song in Kazui's voice have affected the way that Yowamushi Montblanc has changed from its original GUMI version to be even more self-hating in one's (impossible?) love for another person.

And of course, the obligatory I hope DECO*27 is happy and not overworking himself...he and his team have a lot to say in their artwork, and I hope all of us continue to support them :D
